# Default indexes — the most-tested gotcha

## Why it exists

- pandas has a **built-in row index**; Spark DataFrames **do not** (no inherent order)
- Pandas-on-Spark must **fabricate** one — the strategy has perf + correctness effects

## Three strategies (`compute.default_index_type`)

- **`sequence`** — one executor counts `0,1,2…` — sequential but **non-distributed** (slow)
- **`distributed-sequence`** *(default)* — parallel from partition offsets — sequential, slight overhead — **the right answer**
- **`distributed`** — monotonic ids — cheapest, fully parallel — **not sequential** (`0, 1, 8589934592…`)

## The trap

- Under `distributed`, index-dependent pandas code (`loc`, index joins, `.iloc`) **silently breaks**
